{"id":"2107.00043","submitter":"Adam Noble","authors":"Teyoun Kang, Adam Noble, Samuel R. Yoffe, Dino A. Jaroszynski, and Min\n  Sup Hur","title":"Radiation reaction and the acceleration-dependent mass increase of a\n  charged sphere undergoing uniform acceleration","comments":"9 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Physics Letters A 407 (2021) 127445","doi":"10.1016/j.physleta.2021.127445","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Photon emission from a uniformly accelerated charge is among the most\nmysterious physical phenomena. Theories based on the Lorentz-Abraham-Dirac\nequation mostly conclude that a uniformly accelerated point charge cannot feel\nradiation reaction. Such a conclusion suggests that the origin of the photon\nenergy is unclear. In this paper, we determine the self-force of a uniformly\naccelerated charged sphere using the Lorentz force equation, with an assumption\nthat the sphere is Lorentz-contracted during the acceleration. For large\nacceleration, the calculated self-force converges to the radiation reaction\n(given by the Larmor formula) via a new factor $\\gamma_{a}$, which describes an\nacceleration-dependent increase in the effective mass. This increased mass\nmakes it harder to accelerate the particle (compared to a point-charge), which\nmeans more energy should be provided to the particle in order to get the\nexpected acceleration. This extra energy can be interpreted as the origin of\nthe photon energy.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Jun 2021 18:06:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-02"}
